28/10/2002
SARAJEVO, Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) -- Paddy Ashdown, the chief international officer in BiH, told reporters Sunday (27 October) that the affair involving the sale of spare parts to Iraq could prove to be bigger than originally thought.
"It's going to be regional and it's going to extend into areas which will surprise us," he said.
Observers have been speculating for some time that the components of the former Yugoslav military-industrial complex may have continued to operate as a network despite the disintegration of the country.
Republika Srpska's (RS) Supreme Defence Council meets Monday to discuss the Orao company's involvement and to decide whether RS Army Chief of Staff Gen Novica Simic will be forced to assume responsibility for violating the UN trade embargo against Iraq.
Yugoslav President Vojislav Kostunica meanwhile has summoned top federal officials to discuss reports suggesting that the state-run company Jugoimport illegally sold arms and other military equipment to Iraq.
(OHR, Tanjug, B92, Danas - 28/10/02;
AFP, RTRS, PBS BiH, Onasa, BiH Press, BH Radio, BBC, Pobjeda - 27/10/02)
